[1mNAME[0m[m
       screen - screen manager with VT100/ANSI terminal emulation[m
[m
[m
[m
[1mSYNOPSIS[0m[m
       [1mscreen[0m [ [1m-[0m[4moptions[24m ] [ [4mcmd[24m [ [4margs[24m ] ][m
       [1mscreen[0m [1m-r[0m [[[4mpid[24m[1m.[0m][4mtty[24m[[1m.[0m[4mhost[24m]][m
       [1mscreen[0m [1m-r[0m [4msessionowner[24m[1m/[0m[[[4mpid[24m[1m.[0m][4mtty[24m[[1m.[0m[4mhost[24m]][m

[m
[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       [4mScreen[24m is a full-screen window manager that multiplexes a physical terminal between several[m
       processes (typically interactive shells).  Each virtual terminal provides the functions  of[m
       a  DEC  VT100  terminal and, in addition, several control functions from the ISO 6429 (ECMA[m
       48, ANSI X3.64) and ISO 2022 standards (e.g. insert/delete line and  support  for  multiple[m

There  is  a  scrollback history buffer for each virtual terminal and a[m
       copy-and-paste mechanism that allows moving text regions between windows.[m
[m
       When [4mscreen[24m is called, it creates a single window with a shell in it (or the specified com-[m
       mand)  and then gets out of your way so that you can use the program as you normally would.[m
       Then, at any time, you can create new (full-screen) windows with  other  programs  in  them[m
       (including more shells), kill existing windows, view a list of windows, turn output logging[m
       on and off, copy-and-paste text  between  windows,  view  the  scrollback  history,  switch[m
       between windows in whatever manner you wish, etc. All windows run their programs completely[m
       independent of each other. Programs continue to run when their window is currently not vis-[m
       ible  and  even when the whole [4mscreen[24m session is detached from the user's terminal.  When a[m
       progra

m terminates, [4mscreen[24m (per default) kills the window that contained it.  If this  win-[m
       dow  was  in the foreground, the display switches to the previous window; if none are left,[m
       [4mscreen[24m exits.[m
[m
       Everything you type is sent to the program running in the current window.  The only  excep-[m
       tion to this is the one keystroke that is used to initiate a command to the window manager.[m
       By default, each command begins with a control-a (abbreviated C-a from now on), and is fol-[m
       lowed  by one other keystroke.  The command character and all the key bindings can be fully[m
       customized to be anything you like, though they are always two characters in length.[m
[m
       [4mScreen[24m does not understand the prefix "C-" to mean control.  Please use the caret  notation[m
       ("^A"  instead  of "C-a") as arguments to e.g. the [4mescape[24m command or the [4m-e[24m option.  [4mScreen[24m[m
       will also print out c

caret notation.[m
[m
       The standard way to create a new window is to type "C-a c".  This creates a new window run-[m
       ning  a  shell  and  switches  to  that  window immediately, regardless of the state of the[m
       process running in the current window.  Similarly, you can create a new window with a  cus-[m
       tom command in it by first binding the command to a keystroke (in your .screenrc file or at[m
       the "C-a :" command line) and then using it just like the "C-a c"  command.   In  addition,[m
       new windows can be created by running a command like:[m
[m
              screen emacs prog.c[m
[m
       from  a shell prompt within a previously created window.  This will not run another copy of[m
:[K

[4mscreen[24m, but will instead supply the command name and its arguments to  the  window  manager[m
       (specified in the $STY environment variable) who will use it to create the new window.  The[m
       above example would start the emacs editor (editing prog.c) and switch to its window.[m
[m
       If "/etc/utmp" is writable by [4mscreen[24m, an appropriate record will be written  to  this  file[m
       for  each  window,  and  removed when the window is terminated.  This is useful for working[m
       with "talk", "script", "shutdown", "rsend", "sccs" and other similar programs that use  the[m
       utmp  file to determine who you are. As long as [4mscreen[24m is active on your terminal, the ter-[m
       minal's own record is removed from the utmp file. See also "C-a L".[m
[m
[m
[m
[1mGETTING[0m [1mSTARTED[0m[m
       Before you begin to use [4mscreen[24m you'll need to make sure you have  correctly  selected  your[m
       terminal  type, just as you

other termcap/terminfo program.  (You can do this[m
       by using [4mtset[24m for example.)[m
[m
       If you're impatient and want to get started without doing a lot more  reading,  you  should[m
       remember  this  one  command:  "C-a ?".  Typing these two characters will display a list of[m
       the available [4mscreen[24m commands and their bindings. Each keystroke is discussed in  the  sec-[m
       tion  "DEFAULT KEY BINDINGS". The manual section "CUSTOMIZATION" deals with the contents of[m
       your .screenrc.[m
[m
       If your terminal is a "true" auto-margin terminal (it doesn't allow the  last  position  on[m
       the  screen  to  be  updated without scrolling the screen) consider using a version of your[m
       terminal's termcap that has automatic margins turned [4moff[24m. This will ensure an accurate  and[m
       optimal  update  of  the  screen in all circumstances. Most terminals nowadays have "magic"[m
       margins (automatic margins plus usa

umn). This is the VT100 style type and  per-[m
       fectly  suited  for [4mscreen[24m.  If all you've got is a "true" auto-margin terminal [4mscreen[24m will[m
       be content to use it, but updating a character put into the last position on the screen may[m
       not  be possible until the screen scrolls or the character is moved into a safe position in[m
       some other way. This delay can be shortened by using a terminal with insert-character capa-[m
       bility.[m

DEFAULT[0m [1mKEY[0m [1mBINDINGS[0m[m
       As mentioned, each [4mscreen[24m command consists of a "C-a" followed by one other character.  For[m
       your convenience, all commands that are bound to lower-case letters are also bound to their[m
       control character counterparts (with the exception of "C-a a"; see below), thus, "C-a c" as[m
       well  as  "C-a  C-c"  can  be  used  to  create a window. See section "CUSTOMIZATION" for a[m
       description of the command.[m
[m
[m
       The following table shows the default key bindings:[m
[m

[1mC-a[0m [1m'[0m       (select)      Prompt for a window name or number to switch to.[m
[m
       [1mC-a[0m [1m"[0m       (windowlist -b)[m
                                 Present a list of all windows for selection.[m
[m
       [1mC-a[0m [1m0[0m       (select 0)[m
        [1m...[0m           ...[m
       [1mC-a[0m [1m9[0m       (select 9)[m

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       [4mScreen[24m is a full-screen window manager that multiplexes a physical terminal between several[m
       processes (typically interactive shells).  Each virtual terminal provides the functions  of[m
       a  DEC  VT100  terminal and, in addition, several control functions from the ISO 6429 (ECMA[m
       48, ANSI X3.64) and ISO 2022 standards (e.g. insert/delete line and  support  for  multiple[m

There  is  a  scrollback history buffer for each virtual terminal and a[m
       copy-and-paste mechanism that allows moving text regions between windows.[m
[m
       When [4mscreen[24m is called, it creates a single window with a shell in it (or the specified com-[m
       mand)  and then gets out of your way so that you can use the program as you normally would.[m
       Then, at any time, you can create new (full-screen) windows with  other  programs  in  them[m
       (including more shells), kill existing windows, view a list of windows, turn output logging[m
       on and off, copy-and-paste text  between  windows,  view  the  scrollback  history,  switch[m
       between windows in whatever manner you wish, etc. All windows run their programs completely[m
       independent of each other. Programs continue to run when their window is currently not vis-[m
       ible  and  even when the whole [4mscreen[24m session is detached from the user's terminal.  When a[m
       progra

es, [4mscreen[24m (per default) kills the window that contained it.  If this  win-[m
       dow  was  in the foreground, the display switches to the previous window; if none are left,[m
       [4mscreen[24m exits.[m
[m
       Everything you type is sent to the program running in the current window.  The only  excep-[m
       tion to this is the one keystroke that is used to initiate a command to the window manager.[m
       By default, each command begins with a control-a (abbreviated C-a from now on), and is fol-[m
       lowed  by one other keystroke.  The command character and all the key bindings can be fully[m
       customized to be anything you like, though they are always two characters in length.[m
[m
       [4mScreen[24m does not understand the prefix "C-" to mean control.  Please use the caret  notation[m
       ("^A"  instead  of "C-a") as arguments to e.g. the [4mescape[24m command or the [4m-e[24m option.  [4mScreen[24m[m
       will also print out control cha

caret notation.[m
[m
       The standard way to create a new window is to type "C-a c".  This creates a new window run-[m
       ning  a  shell  and  switches  to  that  window immediately, regardless of the state of the[m
       process running in the current window.  Similarly, you can create a new window with a  cus-[m
       tom command in it by first binding the command to a keystroke (in your .screenrc file or at[m
       the "C-a :" command line) and then using it just like the "C-a c"  command.   In  addition,[m
       new windows can be created by running a command like:[m
[m
              screen emacs prog.c[m
[m
       from  a shell prompt within a previously created window.  This will not run another copy of[m
:[K

[4mscreen[24m, but will instead supply the command name and its arguments to  the  window  manager[m
       (specified in the $STY environment variable) who will use it to create the new window.  The[m
       above example would start the emacs editor (editing prog.c) and switch to its window.[m
[m
       If "/etc/utmp" is writable by [4mscreen[24m, an appropriate record will be written  to  this  file[m
       for  each  window,  and  removed when the window is terminated.  This is useful for working[m
       with "talk", "script", "shutdown", "rsend", "sccs" and other similar programs that use  the[m
       utmp  file to determine who you are. As long as [4mscreen[24m is active on your terminal, the ter-[m
       minal's own record is removed from the utmp file. See also "C-a L".[m

       tion  "DEFAULT KEY BINDINGS". The manual section "CUSTOMIZATION" deals with the contents of[m
       your .screenrc.[m
[m
       If your terminal is a "true" auto-margin terminal (it doesn't allow the  last  position  on[m
       the  screen  to  be  updated without scrolling the screen) consider using a version of your[m
       terminal's termcap that has automatic margins turned [4moff[24m. This will ensure an accurate  and[m
       optimal  update  of  the  screen in all circumstances. Most terminals nowadays have "magic"[m
       margins (automatic margins plus usa

umn). This is the VT100 style type and  per-[m
       fectly  suited  for [4mscreen[24m.  If all you've got is a "true" auto-margin terminal [4mscreen[24m will[m
       be content to use it, but updating a character put into the last position on the screen may[m
       not  be possible until the screen scrolls or the character is moved into a safe position in[m
       some other way. This delay can be shortened by using a terminal with insert-character capa-[m
       bility.[m
